  <!-- ACCORDION: WHY SHARKNINJA -->
  <section class="accordion" aria-label="Why SharkNinja">
    <button class="acc-head" aria-expanded="false">
      <span>Why SharkNinja?</span>
    </button>
    <div class="acc-panel" hidden>
      <p>
        SharkNinja’s “<em>Outrageously Extraordinary</em>” mindset resonates with how I design:
        never stopping at “good enough.” In a recent chat with Sophia Gutfreund (Associate Brand Manager),
        she talked about how SharkNinja pairs radical innovation with real-world usefulness and that's how they create products
        people didn’t know they needed. That’s the bar I aim for when designing intuitive digital experiences. 
      </p>
      
      <p class="callout">
  <strong>Why I'm interested in SharkNinja:</strong> Companion apps that extend the experience of physical products.
</p>
      <p>
        My Architectural Studies background shaped how I think about how physical spaces and objects impact people. HCI
        sharpened my understanding of how to evaluate people moving through digital systems. At SharkNinja, those perspectives converge 
        creating digital experiences that enhance innovative appliances represents exactly the kind of impactful, three-dimensional UX work I want to pursue.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>



  <!-- ACCORDION: WHY ME (WITH NESTED CARDS) -->
  <section class="accordion" aria-label="Why me">
    <button class="acc-head" aria-expanded="false">
      <span>Why me?</span>
    </button>
    
    <div class="acc-panel" hidden>
      <div class="grid">
        
        <article class="mini-card">
          <h3>Dreaming Big</h3>
          <p>
         After two years in Spain on a Fulbright grant, I returned to Tufts as an International Student Advisor. The 
work was meaningful, but I couldn’t ignore the poorly designed systems that made simple tasks harder for 
students. Instead of settling for frustration, I began postgraduate classes in Human-Computer Interaction 
to learn how to design better experiences for the people I served. Nine months later, I left my job, moved 
to London, and enrolled in an MSc in HCI Design. This decision mirrors SharkNinja’s drive to challenge 
the status quo. Today, I design digital experiences shaped by firsthand insight into user pain points, 
creating systems that anticipate problems before they arise, just as SharkNinja does with every product.


          </p>
          <div class="tag">Rarely Satisfied</div>
        </article>
        
        
           <article class="mini-card">
          <h3>Working with Ambiguity</h3>
          <p><strong>Memento (AI journaling app):</strong> 
          As Product Designer for Memento, an AI-powered journaling app, 
the founder approached me with a vague concept and no existing framework. 
Rather than waiting for perfect clarity, I took ownership 
of the entire design process: creating information architecture, wireframes, high-fidelity designs, and interactive prototypes in Figma. 
Currently conducting usability testing to inform design iterations, 
I've learned to validate decisions through user feedback 
rather than attachment to initial ideas. 
This experience taught me to embrace pivoting 
and move forward with conviction even when requirements aren't perfectly defined.

          </p>
          <div class="tag">Progress over perfection</div>
        </article>

        <article class="mini-card">
          <h3>Understanding the Client</h3>
          <p><strong>Pelly (SaaS, Wales):</strong> 
          At Pelly, a Wales-based SaaS startup, I served as Project Lead and UX Designer for their "Pelly for Federations" tool. Working remotely with the client, I developed a compliance checklist feature tailored to Welsh Cymru Premier regulations. Designing flows and interface components specifically for administrative accuracy, pilot tests showed improved form completion rates. This project required balancing client needs, regulatory requirements, and user capabilities, reinforcing that attention to detail in compliance critical features directly impacts user success</p>
          <div class="tag">Details make the difference</div>
        </article>
        
          <article class="mini-card">
          <h3>Collaboration is Key</h3>
          <p>In every project and every office team that I’ve been a part of, collaboration has been essential. At Memento, our small, but mighty, team of three works closely to ensure that designs remain implementable while maintaining visual and functional integrity. At the outset of the project, I conducted semi structured interviews to make sure that I was designing with real users in mind rather than making assumptions. </p>
         <p>My experience advising over 600 international students at Tufts reinforced the importance of clear, direct communication. I needed to translate complex visa regulations into actionable guidance while working closely with my team in order to effectively handle our large caseloads. These same skills: clarity, collaboration, and openness to feedback translate directly to design work, where I share openly, invite constructive critique, and quickly course-correct when something isn't working.</p>
          <div class="tag">Winning is a team sport</div>
            <div class="tag">Communicating for impact</div>
        </article>



      
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

